---
import { Code } from "astro:components";
import GuideLayout from "../../components/GuideLayout.astro";

const test = `import gleam/json
import gleam/option.{Some}
import gleeunit/should

import watershed/sluice_js
import watershed_js

pub fn two_surveyors_converge_test() {
  let sluice = sluice_js.start(tenant: "survey-co", document: "bench-book")
  let doc_a = sluice_js.connect(sluice, "surveyor-ada")
  let doc_b = sluice_js.connect(sluice, "surveyor-boaz")
  sluice_js.settle(sluice)              // complete both handshakes

  let survey_a = watershed_js.root(doc_a)
  let survey_b = watershed_js.root(doc_b)

  // Concurrent readings, including a same-station race.
  watershed_js.set(survey_a, "station-7", json.float(3.2))
  watershed_js.set(survey_b, "station-9", json.float(1.85))
  watershed_js.set(survey_a, "station-4", json.float(2.0))
  watershed_js.set(survey_b, "station-4", json.float(2.4))
  sluice_js.settle(sluice)              // deliver every edit everywhere

  // Uncontested writes land on both replicas.
  watershed_js.get(survey_b, "station-7")
  |> should.equal(Some(json.float(3.2)))

  // Both surveyors agree on the contested station — deterministically,
  // no polling, no server, no timing accident.
  watershed_js.get(survey_a, "station-4")
  |> should.equal(watershed_js.get(survey_b, "station-4"))
}`;

const race = `// Script the race instead of hoping for a schedule: deliver frames on demand.
watershed_js.set(watershed_js.root(doc_a), "station-4", json.float(2.0))
watershed_js.set(watershed_js.root(doc_b), "station-4", json.float(2.4))

sluice_js.step(sluice)     // deliver exactly one frame
sluice_js.settle(sluice)   // then drain the rest to quiescence`;
---

<GuideLayout
  slug="testing"
  description="Step six of the watershed build guide: the sluice is an in-memory levee that runs the real runtime and real server sequencing over an injected transport, so you can write deterministic multi-client convergence tests with explicit delivery and no infrastructure."
>
  <div class="g-block">
    <h2>Prove convergence without a server</h2>
    <p>
      A multiplayer app’s core claim is that every client ends up in the same
      state. Testing that used to mean two browser tabs and a live server. The
      <strong>sluice</strong> replaces both: an in-memory levee — a
      deterministic, single-process stand-in for the server.
    </p>
    <p>
      Crucially, it isn’t a mock. It runs the <em>real</em> runtime — the same
      codecs, pending queues, resubmit, and reconnect catch-up — over an injected
      transport, and the <em>real</em> server sequencing. A passing sluice test
      exercises production code paths end to end; it just supplies its own
      network.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="g-block">
    <h2>Delivery is explicit</h2>
    <p>
      The trick that makes convergence testable is that nothing is delivered
      until you say so. Ops sequence the moment they’re submitted, but arrive
      only when you call <code>settle</code> (deliver until quiescent) or
      <code>step</code> (deliver one frame). Races stop being timing accidents
      and become a sequence of calls.
    </p>
    <span class="g-file">test/convergence_test.gleam</span>
    <figure class="g-code">
      <Code code={test} lang="gleam" theme="css-variables" />
    </figure>
  </div>

  <div class="g-block">
    <h2>Script the race</h2>
    <p>
      When you need a specific interleaving — “both surveyors write
      <code>station-4</code>, deliver B’s frame first” — <code>step</code>
      delivers one frame at a time so you control the order the sequencer sees:
    </p>
    <figure class="g-code">
      <Code code={race} lang="gleam" theme="css-variables" />
    </figure>
    <div class="g-note">
      <p>
        <strong>More controls.</strong> <code>pause</code> / <code>resume</code>
        (on the erlang <code>sluice</code>) hold a client’s frames to script
        delivery order across clients, and <code>advance(ms)</code> moves the
        sluice’s logical clock so presence TTL expiry is testable without ever
        sleeping. The erlang <code>watershed/sluice</code> mirrors
        <code>sluice_js</code> call for call.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="g-block">
    <h2>That’s the loop</h2>
    <p>
      Connect a document, give it a typed schema, choose a merge model per slot,
      add ripples for the ephemeral tier, wire it to Lustre, and lock the whole
      thing down with deterministic convergence tests. Bench Book is small, but
      the shape is the shape of any real watershed app.
    </p>
    <p>
      The <a href="https://github.com/tylerbutler/watershed/tree/main/examples">
      examples</a> take it from here: <code>sudoku_lustre</code> is the full
      typed-and-presence build, <code>scoreboard_cli</code> shows the record
      schema layer, and each ships a real sluice convergence test you can read.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="g-out">
    <span class="annot">You can now</span>
    <p>
      Write multi-client convergence tests that run under <code>gleam test</code>
      with no infrastructure — deterministic, scriptable, and exercising the same
      code that runs in production.
    </p>
  </div>
</GuideLayout>
